HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) is the standard markup language used to create web pages. HTML documents are structured using a set of elements and tags that define the content and layout of a web page. Here's a basic structure of an HTML document:
<!DOCTYPE html> <!-- Document Type Declaration -->
<html> <!-- The root element that contains all other elements -->
<head> <!-- Contains meta-information about the document -->
    <meta charset="UTF-8"> <!-- Character encoding for the document -->
    <title>Page Title</title> <!-- Title of the web page, displayed in the browser tab -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css"> <!-- Link to an external CSS file -->
</head>
<body> <!-- Contains the visible content of the web page -->
    <header> <!-- Header section (e.g., logo, navigation) -->
        <h1>Main Heading</h1> <!-- Main heading of the page -->
    </header>
    <nav> <!-- Navigation links -->
        <ul>
            <li><a href="home.html">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="about.html">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="contact.html">Contact</a></li>
        </ul>
    </nav>
    <main> <!-- Main content of the web page -->
        <section> <!-- A section of content -->
            <h2>Section Heading</h2>
            <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
            <img src="image.jpg" alt="Description of the image"> <!-- Image element with alternative text -->
        </section>
    </main>
    <footer> <!-- Footer section (e.g., copyright information) -->
        <p>&copy; 2023 Your Website Name</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>


This is a simplified structure of an HTML document. The <!DOCTYPE html> declaration defines the document type, and the <html> element is the root element that contains all other elements. The <head> section contains meta-information, and the <body> section contains the visible content of the web page, including headers, navigation, main content, and a footer. Inside the <body> section, you can use various HTML elements to structure and style your web page as needed.
